[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Statements in Swift don't have to end with a semicolon, however semicolons are required to separate multiple statements written on the same line.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Single-line comments begin with `//` and continue until the end of the current line.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Multiline comments are contained by `/*` and `*/` characters.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Constants (variables which cannot be modified) are declared with the `let` keyword, while variables declared using the `var` keyword can change.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Values must be initialised before they are read.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Variables may infer their type based on the type of the provided initial value.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] If the initial value is set after the value's declaration, a type must be declared explicitly.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Control flow in Swift is managed with if-else, guard, and switch statements, along with while and for-in loops.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] The `if` statements take a Boolean parameter and execute the body of the `if` statement if the condition is true, otherwise it executes the optional `else` body.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] `if-let` syntax provides syntactic sugar for checking for the existence of an optional value and unwrapping it at the same time.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Functions are defined with the `func` keyword.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Function parameters may have names which allow function calls to read like phrases.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] An underscore before the parameter name allows the argument label to be omitted from the call site.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Tuples can be used by functions to return multiple pieces of data at once.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Functions, and anonymous functions known as closures, can be assigned to properties and passed around the program like any other value.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] `guard` statements require that the given condition is true before continuing on past the `guard` statement, otherwise the body of the provided `else` clause is run.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] The `else` clause must exit control of the code block in which the `guard` statement appears.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] `guard` statements are useful for ensuring that certain requirements are met before continuing on with program execution.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] In particular they can be used to create an unwrapped version of an optional value that is guaranteed to be non-nil for the remainder of the enclosing scope.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] `switch` statements compare a value with multiple potential values and then executes an associated code block.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] `switch` statements must be made exhaustive, either by including cases for all possible values or by including a `default` case which is run when the provided value doesn't match any of the other cases.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] `switch` cases do not implicitly fall through, although they may explicitly do so with the `fallthrough` keyword.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Pattern matching can be used in various ways inside `switch` statements.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Swift supports closures, which are self-contained blocks of functionality that can be passed around and used in code, and can also be used as anonymous functions.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Closures can be assigned to variables and constants, and can be passed into other functions or closures as parameters.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Single-expression closures may drop the `return` keyword.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Swift also has a trailing closure syntax, which allows the closure to be written after the end of the function call instead of within the function's parameter list.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Swift will provide shorthand argument names for inline closures, removing the need to explicitly name all of the closures parameters.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Closures may capture values from their surrounding scope.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] The Swift standard library includes unicode-compliant `String` and `Character` types.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] String values can be initialized with a String literal, a sequence of characters surrounded by double quotation marks.
