[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] In Swift, callable objects are defined using `callAsFunction`.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Swift supports five access control levels for symbols: `open`, `public`, `internal`, `fileprivate`, and `private`.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] An important feature in Swift is option types, which allow references or values to operate in a manner similar to the common pattern in C, where a pointer may either refer to a specific value or no value at all.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] This implies that non-optional types cannot result in a null-pointer error; the compiler can ensure this is not possible.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Optional types are created with the `Optional` enum.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] To make an Integer that is nullable, one would use a declaration similar to `var optionalInteger: Optional<Int>`.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] As in C#, Swift also includes syntactic sugar for this, allowing one to indicate a variable is optional by placing a question mark after the type name, `var optionalInteger: Int?`.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Variables or constants that are marked optional either have a value of the underlying type or are `nil`.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Optional types *wrap* the base type, resulting in a different instance.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] `String` and `String?` are fundamentally different types, the former is of type `String` while the latter is an `Optional` that may be holding some `String` value.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] To access the value inside, assuming it is not nil, it must be *unwrapped* to expose the instance inside.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] In this case, the `!` operator unwraps `anOptionalInstance` to expose the instance inside, allowing the method call to be made on it.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] If `anOptionalInstance` is nil, a null-pointer error occurs, terminating the program.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] In this case the runtime calls `someMethod` only if `anOptionalInstance` is not nil, suppressing the error.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] A `?` must be placed after every optional property.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] If any of these properties are nil the entire expression evaluates as nil.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] The origin of the term *chaining* comes from the more common case where several method calls/getters are chained together.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Swift's use of optionals allows the compiler to use static dispatch because the unwrapping action is called on a defined instance (the wrapper), versus occurring in a runtime dispatch system.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] In many object-oriented languages, objects are represented internally in two parts.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] The object is stored as a block of data placed on the heap, while the name (or "handle") to that object is represented by a pointer.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Objects are passed between methods by copying the value of the pointer, allowing the same underlying data on the heap to be accessed by anyone with a copy.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] In contrast, basic types like integers and floating-point values are represented directly; the handle contains the data, not a pointer to it, and that data is passed directly to methods by copying.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] These styles of access are termed *pass-by-reference* in the case of objects, and *pass-by-value* for basic types.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Both concepts have their advantages and disadvantages.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Objects are useful when the data is large, like the description of a window or the contents of a document.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] In these cases, access to that data is provided by copying a 32- or 64-bit value, versus copying an entire data structure.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] However, smaller values like integers are the same size as pointers (typically both are one word), so there is no advantage to passing a pointer, versus passing the value.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Swift offers built-in support for objects using either pass-by-reference or pass-by-value semantics, the former using the `class` declaration and the latter using `struct`.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Structs in Swift have almost all the same features as classes: methods, implementing protocols and using the extension mechanisms.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] For this reason, Apple terms all data generically as *instances*, versus objects or values.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Structs do not support inheritance, however.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] The programmer is free to choose which semantics are more appropriate for each data structure in the application.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Larger structures like windows would be defined as classes, allowing them to be passed around as pointers.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Smaller structures, like a 2D point, can be defined as structs, which will be pass-by-value and allow direct access to their internal data with no indirection or reference counting.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] The performance improvement inherent to the pass-by-value concept is such that Swift uses these types for almost all common data types, including `Int` and `Double`, and types normally represented by objects, like `String` and `Array`.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Using value types can result in significant performance improvements in user applications as well.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] `Array`, `Dictionary`, and `Set` all utilize copy on write so that their data are copied only if and when the program attempts to change a value in them.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] This means that the various accessors have what is in effect a pointer to the same data storage.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] So while the data is physically stored as one instance in memory, at the level of the application, these values are separate and physical separation is enforced by copy on write only if needed.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Extensions add new functionality to an existing type, without the need to subclass or even have access to the original source code.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Extensions can add new methods, initializers, computed properties, subscripts, and protocol conformances.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] An example might be to add a spell checker to the base `String` type, which means all instances of `String` in the program gain the ability to spell-check.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] The system is also widely used as an organizational technique, allowing related code to be gathered into library-like extensions.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Extensions are declared with the `extension` keyword.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Protocols promise that a particular type implements a set of methods or properties, meaning that other instances in the system can call those methods on any instance implementing that protocol.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] This is often used in modern object-oriented languages as a substitute for multiple inheritance, although the feature sets are not entirely similar.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] In Objective-C, and most other languages implementing the protocol concept, it is up to the programmer to ensure that the required methods are implemented in each class.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Swift adds the ability to add these methods using extensions, and to use generic programming (generics) to implement them.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Combined, these allow protocols to be written once and support a wide variety of instances.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Also, the extension mechanism can be used to add protocol conformance to an object that does not list that protocol in its definition.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Extensions can be used to add protocol conformance to types.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Protocols themselves can also be extended to provide default implementations of their requirements.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] It does not matter what concrete type of `someSortOfPrintableInstance` is, the compiler will ensure that it conforms to the protocol and thus this code is safe.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] This syntax also means that collections can be based on protocols also, like `let printableArray = [any Printable]`.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Both extensions and protocols are used extensively in Swift's standard library; in Swift 5.9, approximately 1.2 percent of all symbols within the standard library were protocols, and another 12.3 percent were protocol requirements or default implementations.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] For instance, Swift uses extensions to add the `Equatable` protocol to many of their basic types, like Strings and Arrays, allowing them to be compared with the `==` operator.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] This function defines a method that works on any instance conforming to `Equatable`, providing a *not equals* operator.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Any instance, class or struct, automatically gains this implementation simply by conforming to `Equatable`.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Protocols, extensions, and generics can be combined to create sophisticated APIs.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] For example, constraints allow types to conditionally adopt protocols or methods based on the characteristics of the adopting type.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Swift 5.5 introduced structured concurrency into the language.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Structured concurrency uses Async/await syntax similar to Kotlin, JavaScript, and Rust.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] An async function is defined with the `async` keyword after the parameter list.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] When calling an async function the `await` keyword must be written before the function to indicate that execution will potentially suspend while calling function.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] While a function is suspended the program may run some other concurrent function in the same program.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] This syntax allows programs to clearly call out potential suspension points and avoid a version of the Pyramid of Doom caused by the previously widespread use of closure callbacks.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] The `async let` syntax allows multiple functions to run in parallel.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] `await` is again used to mark the point at which the program will suspend to wait for the completion of the `async` functions called earlier.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Swift uses the Actor model to isolate mutable state, allowing different tasks to mutate shared state in a safe manner.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Actors are declared with the `actor` keyword and are reference types, like classes.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Only one task may access the mutable state of an actor at the same time.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Actors may access and mutate their own internal state freely, but code running in separate tasks must mark each access with the `await` keyword to indicate that the code may suspend until other tasks finish accessing the actor's state.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] On Apple systems, Swift uses the same runtime as the extant Objective-C system, but requires iOS 7 or macOS 10.9 or higher.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] It also depends on Grand Central Dispatch.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Swift and Objective-C code can be used in one program, and by extension, C and C++ also.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Beginning in Swift 5.9, C++ code can be used directly from Swift code.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] In the case of Objective-C, Swift has considerable access to the object model, and can be used to subclass, extend and use Objective-C code to provide protocol support.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] The converse is not true: a Swift class cannot be subclassed in Objective-C.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] To aid development of such programs, and the re-use of extant code, Xcode 6 and higher offers a semi-automated system that builds and maintains a *bridging header* to expose Objective-C code to Swift.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] This takes the form of an additional header file that simply defines or imports all of the Objective-C symbols that are needed by the project's Swift code.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] At that point, Swift can refer to the types, functions, and variables declared in those imports as though they were written in Swift.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Objective-C code can also use Swift code directly, by importing an automatically maintained header file with Objective-C declarations of the project's Swift symbols.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] For instance, an Objective-C file in a mixed project called "MyApp" could access Swift classes or functions with the code `#import "MyApp-Swift.h"`.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Not all symbols are available through this mechanism, however—use of Swift-specific features like generic types, non-object optional types, sophisticated enums, or even Unicode identifiers may render a symbol inaccessible from Objective-C.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Swift also has limited support for *attributes*, metadata that is read by the development environment, and is not necessarily part of the compiled code.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Like Objective-C, attributes use the `@` syntax, but the currently available set is small.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] One example is the `@IBOutlet` attribute, which marks a given value in the code as an *outlet*, available for use within Interface Builder (IB).
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] An *outlet* is a device that binds the value of the on-screen display to an object in code.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] On non-Apple systems, Swift does not depend on an Objective-C runtime or other Apple system libraries; a set of Swift "Corelib" implementations replace them.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] These include a "swift-corelibs-foundation" to stand in for the Foundation Kit, a "swift-corelibs-libdispatch" to stand in for the Grand Central Dispatch, and an "swift-corelibs-xctest" to stand in for the XCTest APIs from Xcode.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] As of 2019, with Xcode 11, Apple has also added a major new UI paradigm called SwiftUI.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] SwiftUI replaces the older Interface Builder paradigm with a new declarative development paradigm.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Swift uses Automatic Reference Counting (ARC) to manage memory.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Every instance of a class or closure maintains a reference count which keeps a running tally of the number of references the program is holding on to.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] When this count reaches 0 the instance is deallocated.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] This automatic deallocation removes the need for a garbage collector as instances are deallocated as soon as they are no longer needed.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] A *strong reference cycle* can occur if two instances each strongly reference each other (e.g.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Since neither instances reference count can ever reach zero neither is ever deallocated, resulting in a memory leak.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Swift provides the keywords `weak` and `unowned` to prevent strong reference cycles.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] These keywords allow an instance to be referenced without incrementing its reference count.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] `weak` references must be optional variables, since they can change and become `nil`.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Attempting to access an `unowned` value that has already been deallocated results in a runtime error.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] A closure within a class can also create a strong reference cycle by capturing self references.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] A key element of the Swift system is its ability to be cleanly debugged and run within the development environment, using a read–eval–print loop (REPL), giving it interactive properties more in common with the scripting abilities of Python than traditional system programming languages.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] The REPL is further enhanced with playgrounds, interactive views running within the Xcode environment or Playgrounds app that respond to code or debugger changes on-the-fly.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Playgrounds allow programmers to add in Swift code along with markdown documentation.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Programmers can step through code and add breakpoints using LLDB either in a console or an IDE like Xcode.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Because Swift can run on Linux, it is sometimes also used as a server-side language.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Some web frameworks have been developed, such as IBM's Kitura (now discontinued), Perfect, Vapor, and Hummingbird.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] An official "Server APIs" work group has also been started by Apple, with members of the Swift developer community playing a central role.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] A second free implementation of Swift that targets Cocoa, Microsoft's Common Language Infrastructure (.NET Framework, now .NET), and the Java and Android platform exists as part of the *Elements Compiler* from RemObjects Software.
[src:swiftui-framework/swift-programming-language] Subsets of Swift have been ported to additional platforms, such as Arduino and Mac OS 9.
[src:swiftui-framework/swiftui] SwiftUI is declarative, contrasting with the imperative syntax used in other Apple development frameworks such as UIKit and AppKit.
[src:swiftui-framework/swiftui] SwiftUI allows for 2D drawing, animations, event handling, widgets, and data binding.
[src:swiftui-framework/swiftui] SwiftUI automatically synchronizes between UI views and data.
[src:swiftui-framework/swiftui] SwiftUI integrates with other Apple technologies, such as Xcode and Swift Playgrounds to provide for real-time previews during editing, alongside support for debugging and other development features.
[src:swiftui-framework/swiftui] SwiftUI allows for interoperability with UIKit and AppKit views via the `UIViewRepresentable` and `NSViewRepresentable` protocols respectively.
[src:swiftui-framework/swiftui] SwiftUI was announced at the company's Worldwide Developers Conference (WWDC) on June 3, 2019, and was added in iOS 13 and macOS Catalina.
[src:swiftui-framework/swiftui] During WWDC 2020 and the iOS 14 release cycle, Apple natively added support for maps with the `Map` view, with an interface based on Apple Maps via MapKit.
[src:swiftui-framework/swiftui] MapKit allows for map annotation and satellite imagery.
[src:swiftui-framework/swiftui] During WWDC 2021 and the iOS 15 release cycle, Apple added the `Canvas` element, adding support for Immediate mode drawing and performant 2D drawing.
[src:swiftui-framework/swiftui] During WWDC 2022 and the iOS 16 release cycle, Apple released Swift Charts, a framework for making customizable and accessible charts.
[src:swiftui-framework/swiftui] During WWDC 2023, Apple announced the Apple Vision Pro, and support for the device was added to SwiftUI, alongside new views for AR content such as `RealityView` and `ImmersiveSpace`.
